time series methods - US Retail example¶

Import Modules¶

In [1]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

import seaborn as sns

Most time series methods come from statsmodels.

In [2]:
import statsmodels.api as sm

Reorganize data¶

Time series methods want the YEAR-MONTH-DAY combined into a single DATE TIME object!!!!

We must combine these three columns together!!!!

The pd.to_datetime() function is really handy and makes datetime conversions quite easy. It will build the date from the 3 columns for us. We do not need to manually combine the columns before creating the date!

In [16]:
us_retail_df['date_dt'] = pd.to_datetime( us_retail_df.loc[:, ['Year', 'Month', 'Day']] )

Time series organization¶

Most time series methods do NOT want to work with DataFrames!!!!

The time series methods want to work with Pandas Series.

We must therefore extract the Series out of the DataFrame.

In [27]:
retail_series = us_retail_df.Employed.copy()
In [28]:
retail_series
Out[28]:
0      13255.8
1      12966.3
2      12938.2
3      13012.3
4      13108.3
        ...   
352    15691.6
353    15775.5
354    15785.9
355    15749.5
356    15611.3
Name: Employed, Length: 357, dtype: float64
In [29]:
retail_series.index
Out[29]:
RangeIndex(start=0, stop=357, step=1)

Time series methods want the Series .index attribute to be a DateTimeIndex. Thus, we must set the datetime object to the Series .index attribute.

In [30]:
retail_series.index = us_retail_df.date_dt
In [31]:
retail_series.index
Out[31]:
DatetimeIndex(['1990-01-01', '1990-02-01', '1990-03-01', '1990-04-01',
               '1990-05-01', '1990-06-01', '1990-07-01', '1990-08-01',
               '1990-09-01', '1990-10-01',
               ...
               '2018-12-01', '2019-01-01', '2019-02-01', '2019-03-01',
               '2019-04-01', '2019-05-01', '2019-06-01', '2019-07-01',
               '2019-08-01', '2019-09-01'],
              dtype='datetime64[ns]', name='date_dt', length=357, freq=None)

The sampling frequency is MONTHLY where the data are collected (or reported) at the START of the MONTH.

Time series methods REQUIRE that we SPECIFY the sampling frequency. Basically you cannot have freq attribute equal to None!!!!

Essentially most time series methods require REGULAR or CONSTANT intervals between observations. Most methods cannot handle IRREGULAR reporting!!!!!!!

We can force a sampling frequency using the Pandas .resample() method. This .resample() method does NOT refer to cross-validation!!! Instead, .resample() allows us to identify the SAMPLING FREQUENCY.

We must also supply a SUMMARY FUNCTION to handle the irregular or multiple observations within the sampling period.

In [32]:
ready_series = retail_series.copy().resample('MS').mean()

Visualizations¶

The Pandas series object can be visualized using the default Pandas plotting methods.

In [36]:
ready_series.plot( figsize=(15, 6) )

plt.show()

Time series methods fundamentally deal with autocorrelated data. Autocorrelation refers to sequential observations are usually related to each other. The autocorrelation can be visualized with a lag plot.

The Pandas plotting function pd.plotting.lag_plot() assembles the data correctly to support visualizing the LAGS relationship.

In [37]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5, 5))

pd.plotting.lag_plot( ready_series, lag=1, ax=ax )

plt.plot( ax.get_xlim(), ax.get_ylim(), 'k--' )

plt.show()

We do not have to just visualize the sequential observations in a lag plot. We can consider 2 lags.

In [38]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5, 5))

pd.plotting.lag_plot( ready_series, lag=2, ax=ax )

plt.plot( ax.get_xlim(), ax.get_ylim(), 'k--' )

plt.show()
In [39]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5, 5))

pd.plotting.lag_plot( ready_series, lag=3, ax=ax )

plt.plot( ax.get_xlim(), ax.get_ylim(), 'k--' )

plt.show()
In [40]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5, 5))

pd.plotting.lag_plot( ready_series, lag=6, ax=ax )

plt.plot( ax.get_xlim(), ax.get_ylim(), 'k--' )

plt.show()
In [41]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5, 5))

pd.plotting.lag_plot( ready_series, lag=12, ax=ax )

plt.plot( ax.get_xlim(), ax.get_ylim(), 'k--' )

plt.show()
In [42]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5, 5))

pd.plotting.lag_plot( ready_series, lag=72, ax=ax )

plt.plot( ax.get_xlim(), ax.get_ylim(), 'k--' )

plt.show()

The lag plots can be summarized into a single figure through the AUTOCORRELATION PLOT.

In [43]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 5))

sm.graphics.tsa.plot_acf( ready_series.values.squeeze(), lags=72, ax=ax )

plt.show()

Time decomposition¶

Separate the TREND from the SEASONAL pattern within the data.

The classic decomposition methods are applied via the sm.tsa.seasonal_decompose().

In [44]:
retail_decompose = sm.tsa.seasonal_decompose( ready_series, model='additive')

Visualize the time series decomposition.

In [45]:
fig = retail_decompose.plot()

The above figure is rather small. The size is increased below.

In [46]:
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = 18,8
plt.show()

fig = retail_decompose.plot()

We can extract the various components. For example, the .seasonal is provided below.

If you subtract the .seasonal component from the raw data or the .observed values you will have the SEASONALLY ADJUSTED observations. Seasonally adjusted means the seasonal component is removed and we are examining the MACRO trend over time.

In [48]:
df_decomp_retail = pd.DataFrame({'observed': retail_decompose.observed,
                                 'seasonal_adjusted': retail_decompose.observed - retail_decompose.seasonal},
                                index=ready_series.index)

We can also visualize the month-to-month variation with the MONTH PLOT.

The function is sm.graphics.tsa.month_plot().

In [51]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 5))

sm.graphics.tsa.month_plot( ready_series, ylabel="Employment", ax=ax )

plt.show()

If we use the entire time series the month plot is clouded by the overall MACRO trend...instead we want to visualize the DETRENDED data.

The DETRENDED data is the .observed attribute minus the .trend attribute. However, the classical additive method has NaN values at the beginning and end of the series.

If we make the MONTH plot using the .seasonal component directly...it's not very interesting from the ADDITIVE decomposition. The seasonal term is assumed to be constant over the years in the classical additive method!

plt.show()

Advanced decompositions¶

We can allow the seasonal pattern to change across years by using more advanced decomposition methods.

In [53]:
from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import STL
In [54]:
retail_stl = STL( ready_series )
In [55]:
retail_stl_fit = retail_stl.fit( )
In [56]:
fig = retail_stl_fit.plot()

We can extract the components just as before, so we can visualize the seasonally adjusted data.

In [57]:
df_stl_retail = pd.DataFrame({"observed": retail_stl_fit.observed,
                              'seasonal_adjusted': retail_stl_fit.observed - retail_stl_fit.seasonal},
                             index=ready_series.index)
In [58]:
sns.relplot(data = df_stl_retail, kind='line', aspect=3.5)

plt.show()

  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

It's easier to create the visuals for the detrended data.

In [60]:
retail_detrend = retail_stl_fit.observed - retail_stl_fit.trend
In [61]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))

sm.graphics.tsa.month_plot( retail_detrend, ylabel='Employment : Detrended', ax = ax)

plt.show()

We can further smooth the detrended data by also subtracting the RESIDUAL or remainder.

In [62]:
retail_detrend_smooth = retail_stl_fit.observed - ( retail_stl_fit.trend + retail_stl_fit.resid )
In [63]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))

sm.graphics.tsa.month_plot( retail_detrend_smooth, ylabel = 'Employment: Smoothed detrended', ax = ax)

plt.show()

We could have just made the above figure using the SEASONAL component directly from the STL decomposition.

In [64]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))

sm.graphics.tsa.month_plot( retail_stl_fit.seasonal, ylabel = 'Employment: Seasonal', ax = ax)

plt.show()

Conclusion¶

The report demonstated organizing the data for time series analysis, exploring the autocorrelation structure, and extracting the seasonal and trend components via decomposition.
